    <item>
      <title>Colonization and Economic Growth: A Visual History in Maps</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/post/3_colonizationgrowth/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 06 Mar 2026 17:32:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/post/3_colonizationgrowth/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;introduction&#34;&gt;Introduction&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;How did centuries of European colonization shape the global economy? The legacy of colonial rule is one of the most studied—and debated—topics in development economics. In this short post, I use interactive maps to visually trace two threads: the spread of colonial rule from the 1500s onward, and the stark differences in economic prosperity across countries today.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;colonization-and-gdp-a-visual-comparison&#34;&gt;Colonization and GDP: A Visual Comparison&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The first map shows which countries were colonies at any point in time—use the slider to scrub through history. The second shows GDP per capita today.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>IV method and Shift-Share instruments</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/post/1_iv_shiftshare/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 17 Oct 2025 11:34:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/post/1_iv_shiftshare/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;instrumental-variable-approach-for-causal-inference&#34;&gt;Instrumental Variable approach for Causal Inference&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;If we believe that a variable &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex-mathml&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;X&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;X&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex-html&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;base&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;strut&#34; style=&#34;height:0.6833em;&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;mord mathnormal&#34; style=&#34;margin-right:0.07847em;&#34;&gt;X&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; causes (or affects) another variable &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex-mathml&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;Y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex-html&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;base&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;strut&#34; style=&#34;height:0.6833em;&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;mord mathnormal&#34; style=&#34;margin-right:0.22222em;&#34;&gt;Y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, we are often interested in studying how much the value of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex-mathml&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;Y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex-html&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;base&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;strut&#34; style=&#34;height:0.6833em;&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;mord mathnormal&#34; style=&#34;margin-right:0.22222em;&#34;&gt;Y&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; changes if we make a small &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex-mathml&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;δ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\delta x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex-html&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;base&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;strut&#34; style=&#34;height:0.6944em;&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;mord mathnormal&#34; style=&#34;margin-right:0.03785em;&#34;&gt;δ&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;mord mathnormal&#34;&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; change in &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex-mathml&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;X&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;X&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex-html&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;base&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;strut&#34; style=&#34;height:0.6833em;&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;mord mathnormal&#34; style=&#34;margin-right:0.07847em;&#34;&gt;X&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. For example, how much do people dislike traffic on their street can be measured by decrease in house prices in response to increase in street traffic. The statistical technique most commonly used to answer causal questions is the linear regression &#xD;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;inline-note-marker&#34; data-note-id=&#34;1&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;sup class=&#34;note-ref&#34;&gt;[1]&lt;/sup&gt;&#xD;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&#xD;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
